+# Wave 14 adversarial review — Planning imports/procurement
+
+Branch reviewed: `fix/wave14-imports`  
+Patch reviewed: `git diff origin/main..HEAD`, excluding `_meta/`  
+Review date: 2026-07-10
+
+## Findings
+
+1. **HIGH — the PO rollback regression test does not prove rollback** (`apps/web/app/[locale]/(app)/(modules)/planning/purchase-orders/_actions/import-po.test.ts:237`). The test replaces `withOrgContext` with a callback runner and replaces `createPurchaseOrderCore` with a mock. No PO is ever inserted, no transaction is begun/committed/rolled back, and the final assertion checks only the returned `created` array and absence of the import-job insert. Concrete false-green: change the importer to catch the group-2 failure inside the callback and return `{ created: [], skipped: [], failed }` normally; this test still passes even though real `withOrgContext` would commit group 1. The implementation currently throws correctly at `import-po.ts:230`, but the required persistence proof is absent.
+
+2. **HIGH — the TO rollback regression test has the same false-green** (`apps/web/app/[locale]/(app)/(modules)/planning/transfer-orders/_actions/import-to.test.ts:211`). It mocks both the transaction wrapper and the core, so order 1 never exists in transactional state and the test cannot establish that zero orders commit. Concrete false-green: a normal-return failure response with `created: []` after order 1's independent/committed write satisfies every assertion at lines 233–237. The branch's current import path is one shared context and throws at `import-to.ts:226`, but the acceptance criterion specifically requires proving that order 2 failure leaves no persisted order.
+
+## Per-bug assessment
+
+### N-30 PO `all_or_nothing` — PARTIAL (`import-po.ts:66–247`; test gap at `import-po.test.ts:237`)
+
+The code-level transaction flow is fixed:
+
+- Validation is repeated inside the write transaction at lines 87–93.
+- Every runtime failure in the group loop throws in `all_or_nothing`: duplicate number (140), missing supplier (152), item lookup failure (189), zod failure (205), and core failure (230).
+- The exception escapes the `withOrgContext` callback and is converted to an import response only outside it at lines 243–245, so a real `withOrgContext` rolls back group 1 before the response is returned.
+- The early normal return at lines 77–79 happens before the write transaction; permission failure at line 85 is also before a write. I found no remaining all-or-nothing accumulate-then-normal-return path after a write.
+
+Concrete scenario by inspection: EXT-A core succeeds, EXT-B returns `supplier_blocked`; line 230 throws, preventing lines 233–241 and forcing rollback of EXT-A. However, the added test does not prove persisted state/rollback, as finding 1 explains.
+
+### N-31 TO shared core/transaction — PARTIAL (`create-transfer-order-core.ts:137`; `actions.ts:471`; `import-to.ts:206`; test gap at `import-to.test.ts:211`)
+
+The extraction and call graph are correct:
+
+- `createTransferOrderCore(ctx, input)` accepts the caller's context/client and contains no `withOrgContext`.
+- Public `createTransferOrder` validates, opens `withOrgContext`, and calls the core.
+- `commitToImport` calls the core directly at line 206 using its outer transaction's `ctx`; it does not call the public action.
+- Runtime failures throw at lines 146, 156, 166, 202, and 226. The catch that creates the response is outside `withOrgContext` at lines 240–242. There is no nested `withOrgContext` in the import write path.
+
+Concrete scenario by inspection: TO-A header/lines/audit are written through the outer client; TO-B core returns a failure; line 226 throws through the outer callback, so TO-A and TO-B are both rolled back. The regression test nevertheless cannot prove this persisted outcome because it mocks away both writes and transaction semantics (finding 2).
+
+### N-32 PO import zod validation — FIXED (`import-po-schema.ts:119–137`; `import-po.ts:193–217`)
+
+Each fully grouped payload is `safeParse`d against the exact exported `CreatePurchaseOrderInput` used by single-create before the core is called. The core receives the same constructed fields: number, supplier, draft status, expected date, currency, joined notes, and lines. Zod therefore enforces the 80-character PO number, three-character currency, 2,000-character joined notes, 200-line maximum, UUIDs, numeric formats, UoM length, dates, status, and line numbers. Issues are mapped to source rows, including indexed line issues and note-contributing rows. A 3,000-character note or 201-line group never reaches the core. I found no constructed core field bypassing this parse.
+
+### N-55 supplier locking — FIXED (`create-purchase-order-core.ts:169–184`)
+
+The supplier lookup is org-scoped and uses `FOR UPDATE`; status is checked from the locked row before the PO header insert. If a blocker update owns the row first, this query waits and then sees `blocked` under PostgreSQL READ COMMITTED. If creation owns it first, the block waits until the PO transaction completes. A concurrent block cannot change status between the locked check and insert. The added SQL assertion covers presence of the lock.
+
+### N-62 catch-weight site key — FIXED (`catch-weight-variance.ts:126–184`; migration `477-catch-weight-variance-site-day-key.sql:10–16`)
+
+The aggregate grain is `(item_id, site_id)`, and the upsert conflict target is `(org_id, item_id, site_id, day)`. Migration 477 replaces the old stricter `(org,item,day)` unique index with the per-site unique index and uses `NULLS NOT DISTINCT`, so null-site rows also remain unique. Existing data cannot contain two rows that collide on the new, more-specific key because the old key allowed at most one row for the broader `(org,item,day)` grain. A two-site item yields two aggregate rows and two persisted rows; the DB integration test asserts both. No reserved-keyword alias was introduced (`item_row`, `weighings`, and `scored` are safe).
+
+### N-63 skipped nominal signal — FIXED (`catch-weight-variance.ts:83–117`; integration test in `catch-weight-variance.test.ts`)
+
+Catch-weight weighings with null/non-positive effective nominal are queried separately and surfaced as distinct `(itemId, siteId, reason)` entries with `missing_nominal` or `zero_nominal`; the summary and cron response propagate `skipped`. The integration test inserts a zero-nominal weighing and asserts the returned skipped signal while no variance row is written. They are no longer silently discarded.
+
+## Cross-cutting checks
+
+- No new non-async export exists in a `'use server'` module. New schemas, classes, types, and cores live in non-server siblings; server modules export only async actions.
+- No nested transaction remains in either import write path.
+- No new `tenant_id` or raw org setting appears in the patch.
+- No reserved SQL alias was introduced; `git diff --check` is clean.
+- No new float arithmetic was added for PO money/quantity persistence. Import values are converted to validated decimal strings before SQL numeric casts. Catch-weight percentage conversion to JS numbers is pre-existing output behavior, not money/quantity costing.
+- I found no new reachable normal return after a successful write in either importer. The cores retain `INSERT ... RETURNING` followed by a defensive no-header result; for ordinary PostgreSQL tables a successful insert returns its row, while errors throw. In all-or-nothing imports any core error result is converted to an outer transaction throw.
+
+## Verification evidence
+
+`git -C /Users/mariuszkrawczyk/Projects/monopilot-worktrees/wave14 diff --stat origin/main..HEAD -- . ':(exclude)_meta/**'`:
+
+```text
+.../_actions/create-purchase-order-core.test.ts    | 129 ++++++++++
+.../_actions/create-purchase-order-core.ts         |  11 +-
+.../purchase-orders/_actions/import-po-schema.ts   | 137 +++++++++++
+.../purchase-orders/_actions/import-po.test.ts     |  61 ++++-
+.../planning/purchase-orders/_actions/import-po.ts | 258 ++++++++++++--------
+.../purchase-orders/_actions/po-import-errors.ts   |  12 +
+.../planning/transfer-orders/_actions/actions.ts   |  60 +----
+.../_actions/create-transfer-order-core.ts         | 196 +++++++++++++++
+.../transfer-orders/_actions/import-to.test.ts     |  68 ++++-
+.../planning/transfer-orders/_actions/import-to.ts | 264 +++++++++++++--------
+.../transfer-orders/_actions/to-import-errors.ts   |  12 +
+.../__tests__/catch-weight-variance.test.ts        |  67 ++++-
+.../internal/cron/catch-weight-variance/route.ts   |   1 +
+.../__tests__/catch-weight-variance.unit.test.ts   |  35 +++
+apps/web/lib/cron/catch-weight-variance.ts         |  90 +++++--
+.../477-catch-weight-variance-site-day-key.sql     |  16 ++
+16 files changed, 1111 insertions(+), 306 deletions(-)
+```
+
+Targeted Vitest raw stdout tail (the mandated `task` wrapper is unavailable in this worktree/runtime, so the same targeted command was run directly; build/typecheck were not run per Codex-lane rules):
+
+```text
+ RUN  v4.1.5 /Users/mariuszkrawczyk/Projects/monopilot-worktrees/wave14/apps/web
+
+ Test Files  4 passed (4)
+      Tests  24 passed (24)
+   Start at  13:51:06
+   Duration  235ms (transform 160ms, setup 0ms, import 245ms, tests 22ms, environment 0ms)
+```
+
+VERDICT: fail
+
+Required changes:
+
+1. Replace or supplement the PO all-or-nothing mock-only test with a rollback-aware test that records transactional writes (preferably DB integration): group 1 must be inserted, group 2 must fail at runtime, and a post-transaction query must prove zero matching purchase orders and zero import-job rows persisted.
+2. Add the equivalent rollback-aware TO test: order 1 must actually be written through the shared transaction, order 2 must fail, and post-transaction state must contain neither order nor an import-job row.

